[1] Sierra Leone Ebola-free
Date: Sat 7 Nov 2015
Source: Public Broadcasting System [edited]
http://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/declares-sierra-leone-free-ebola/


Sierra Leone: WHO--Sierra Leone is free of Ebola
--------------------------------------------

[Sierra Leone is now officially free of Ebola.

After 42 days without Ebola virus disease (EVD) cases, Sierra Leone has been declared by the World Health Organization (WHO), on 7 Nov 2015, as being free of EVD, which has plagued the country for the last 18 months. According to President Ernest Bai Koroma, being free of EVD represents a "difficult and turbulent journey." However, lurking in the background is the reality of a continuing EVD outbreak in Sierra Leone's neighboring country, Guinea. While measures have been put into place to restrict the unmonitored crossing of borders, the reality is the border between Guinea and Sierra Leone is still very porous and open to clandestine crossings, leaving open the possibility of a new outbreak.]

Byline: Andrew Mach

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>


[Also see http://www.afro.who.int/en/sierra-leone/press-materials/item/8139-who-commends-sierra-leone-for-stopping-ebola-virus-transmission.html
Today (7 Nov 2015), the World Health Organization declares that Ebola virus transmission has been stopped in Sierra Leone. 42 days, that is 2 Ebola virus incubation cycles, have now passed since the last person confirmed to have Ebola virus disease had a 2nd negative blood test.
Since Sierra Leone recorded the 1st Ebola case in May 2014, a total number of 8704 people were infected and 3589 have died, 221 of them healthcare workers, all of whom we remember on this day" said Dr Anders Nordström, WHO Representative in Sierra Leone.
The country now enters a 90-day period of enhanced surveillance which will run until 5 Feb 2016 and WHO will continue to support Sierra Leone during this period. This new phase is critical for ensuring early detection of any possible new cases of Ebola virus disease. ...-more]

[This is a celebratory time for Sierra Leone, and the world. We hope Guinea will also be Ebola-free soon. It is critical that strict attention to public health precautions be maintained in Sierra Leone and Liberia to retain an Ebola-free status, and Guinea to achieve it. - Mod.LK]

[Sierra Leone deserves to celebrate after all the death and hardship. But unfortunately, the finding of transmission by infected sperm in male survivors and the relapse into Ebola meningitis of the Scottish nurse, both months after they were declared Ebola-free, mean that surveillance and contact tracing need to be redoubled now. There will be tremendous reluctance to report suspect cases, because nobody will want to spoil the party, and by allowing patients to die at home they can be assured of a traditional burial, so opportunities for new infection chains will continue. - Mod.JW]


