[See also Comment in column on right of web page]
Date: 8 Nov 2015
Source: Lancet Infectious Diseases [edited]
http://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(15)00375-8/fulltext

What might post-Ebola health services look like in West Africa?
-------------------------------------------------
The article by Horby et al.(1) provides a concise summary of the impressive amount of research already done on prevention and control of EVD. Available data on latent infections in recovered patients, coupled with new estimates of the number of undetected or unreported cases(2), indicate that EVD should be considered endemic at low frequencies in human populations in West Africa.

What has not been discussed are the precautions to be taken to prevent transmission from emergency trauma victims, obstetric procedures, and other cases of individuals with unknown infection status. It is impractical from economic and logistical perspectives to require all HWs in contact with cases involving haemorrhage or body fluid exposures, to wear full-body PPE routinely.

Assuming that vaccination for HWs and rapid bedside tests for Ebola with laboratory confirmation will soon be available in the 3 countries, and that international aid for strengthened health services will continue to reach hospitals and health centres, it might be prudent to plan along the following lines. Maternity hospitals: routine serology for ebolavirus; if positive, isolate. Closed area with 2 HWs in PPE to decontaminate anyone exposed. If exposure begins before serology result available, treat as a suspect case. Emergency department: install a decontamination area as above to deal with anyone exposed to suspect cases. All: Perform serology asap. Safe burial teams: on standby for suspect cases, rapid confirmatory test essential. Contact tracing for positive cases: vaccination for household members & visitors (not fully effective for 10 days), ring vaccination around index house (early ring vaccination not fully effective)(3); follow-up house visits for fever. Financial & manpower needs: shift staffing and hazard pay. Offer survivors without debilitating sequelae, training & employment as decontamination & burial staff, saving expensive PPE and short shifts. Those on the ground in West Africa will know if there is any interest in this idea among survivors. Level of immunity to be tested monthly, vaccination or reassignment if declining.

Hopefully, these ideas will promote discussion.

I declare no competing interests.
John "Jack" Woodall PhD, Rockefeller Foundation Belem Virus Laboratory, Brazil, NYS DoH, CDC, WHO (retired). Co-founder & Assoc.Ed. ProMED <www.promedmail.org>

Acknowledgement: Joseph Dudley <jpdudley@alaska.edu>
