[4] Suspected, research, vaccine, funding

4 Nov 2015 Guinea: Newborn's Ebola infection adds to Guinea's total
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2015/11/newborns-ebola-infection-adds-guineas-total
[In its weekly update today the WHO said the baby was delivered in an Ebola treatment center in Conakry and is being treated. The child's infection is the 4th reported from the same family in the village of Kondeyah, in Forecariah district.
The newborn's 25-year-old mother, whose Ebola infection was confirmed the previous week, died after giving birth. Ebola infections had also been confirmed in 2 of the woman's other young children whose illnesses were also announced the week before. The WHO warned that those family cases generated a large number of high-risk contacts who are now in their 2nd week of 21-day monitoring.
According to the WHO, the baby's illness is the tenth in the Forecariah branch of a transmission chain that began in Conakry's Ratoma area.
Guinea is monitoring a total of 382 contacts, which include 43 in Conakry and 339 in Forecariah district. Among that group are 141 high-risk contacts, 7 from the capital and the rest from Forecariah.

In Sierra Leone, all contacts linked to the country's last 2 known transmission chains have completed follow-up. Its last patient tested negative for a 2nd time on 25 Sep 2015, and if no further cases are reported, Sierra Leone will reach Ebola-free status on 7 Nov 2015.
The WHO noted that the outbreak region has now reported 5 or fewer cases for 14 consecutive weeks. The overall outbreak number for the 3 affected West African countries is at 28 571 confirmed, probable, or suspected cases, with the number of deaths reaching 11 299."]

[Sierra Leone has now been declared Ebola-free -- see above -- leaving Guinea as the last holdout of cases. Bordering countries must be on guard for re-introduction of virus. -Mod LK]]

6 Nov 2015 Guinea: Ebola mobile suitcase laboratory successfully tested in Guinea
http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2015/11/151106062718.htm
[Field testing has been completed for a new method of rapid diagnosis of Ebola virus disease (EVD) involving a portable field laboratory, which is operated with solar power, and provides remote areas with on-site diagnoses. The detection method is based on rapid identification of viral RNA in oral swabs of suspected infected patients. In trials, an EVD case was detected after 30 minutes.]

5 Nov 2015 Sierra Leone: Headmaster: I feared Ebola would kill blind pupils
http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0376fkd
[According to Didymus Thaimu Kargbo, of Milton Margai School for the Blind, because his students cannot get around without touching people and/or objects, they are particularly at risk. In addition, it is difficult to stop children from playing which often involves touching. (2-minute video on website)]

5 Nov 2015 Sierra Leone: How traditional healers helped defeat Ebola
http://allafrica.com/stories/201511051709.html
[In the beginning of the Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak in May 2014, many residents refused to accept the disease could be treated through Western medicine, and instead sought traditional treatments with herbs, potions and spells provided by the country's estimated 45 000 traditional healers.
According to Richard Mallett of the Overseas Development Institute's Secure Livelihoods Research Consortium (SLRC), "Traditional healers were largely ignored by the state and the international community throughout the early to mid-stages of the Ebola response." Mallett also said the failure to include healers at an earlier stage may have prolonged the outbreak and increased the death toll.
Healers are a significant part of health care for many residents, and excluding them from the delivery of health care alienated not only alienated the healers but also their traditional patients. When Western medicine did not end the outbreak, officials decided to align with the traditional healers and make them part of the social support and publication services providers.]

5 Nov 2015: Sierra Leone beds in against Ebola repeat with UK military's 'hospital in a box'
http://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2015/nov/05/sierra-leone-ebola-uk-military-magazine-wharf-freetown
[Sierra Leone's cross-government response to the Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak led to the creation of a 36-bed "field hospital in a box." The hospital, which will serve as then new frontline response to any future outbreaks, can be deployed and operational anywhere in Sierra Leone within 48 hours.]

4 Nov 2015 Sierra Leone: Doctor once infected with Ebola discusses recovery and 'uncommon heroism'
http://www.dailyprogress.com/news/local/doctor-once-infected-with-ebola-discusses-recovery-and-uncommon-heroism/article_91d5e796-8364-11e5-814b-2ffc6295f0c1.html
[Dr. Crozier has suffered permanent damage from his Ebola virus disease (EVD) infection, including joint pain, hearing loss, short-term memory deficits and an infection in one of his eyes. Since his illness, he has taken an interest in post-EVD effects in survivors, especially the West African survivors. According to Crozier, ""You don't put out 99 percent of a fire. We need a resilient zero, and we need to stay at zero, which is not going to be easy."]

6 Nov 2015 Sierra Leone: Infographic: Counting the economic impact of Ebola
http://www.forbes.com/sites/peteguest/2015/11/06/counting-the-economic-impact-of-ebola/
[Graphs of economic impact of the Ebola virus disease (EVD) on Sierra Leone.]

7 Nov 2015 How the Ebola scare stigmatized African immigrants In the USA
http://www.science20.com/news_articles/how_the_ebola_scare_stigmatized_african_immigrants_in_the_us-158789
[The latest Ebola virus outbreak in West Africa also took its toll socially on one of the fastest growing populations in the United States - African immigrants.
Guy-Lucien Whembolua, a University of Cincinnati assistant professor of Africana studies, reviewed reports in mainstream U.S. media related to African immigrants and the Ebola Virus Disease (EVD). The search turned up 21 news articles that matched the criteria for the study - articles focusing on African immigrants in the U.S. and the Ebola virus.
The researchers found that these African immigrants experienced stigma similar to communities stigmatized by the AIDS epidemic in the '80s. "There was strong discrimination against homosexual men during the AIDS epidemic and laying blame on that population for the spread of the virus," says Whembolua. "Similarly, in the early stages of the Ebola Virus outbreak in West Africa and amid sensationalized reports, we found a fear linked with African immigrants around spreading the disease in the U.S. Some of these populations felt they had to hide their ethnicity in an effort to avoid the stigma."]
8 Nov 2015 USA/West Africa: West Africans allowed to stay in U.S. during Ebola epidemic argue for more time [In 2014, President Obama extended the Temporary Protected Status (originally granted in 2014), to possibly 2016--depending on review of by the US Immigration Service (IMS)--for the native residents of Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone who are already in the US (United States of America].

Vaccine, Research
-----------
4 Nov 2015: Ring vaccination efficacy questioned in Ebola containment
http://vaccinenewsdaily.com/stories/510646577-ring-vaccination-efficacy-questioned-in-ebola-containment
[In a recent study of the efficacy of ring vaccination in West Africa's Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak in Guinea, conducted by scientists at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, they found using ring vaccination at the beginning of the outbreak did not help to contain the virus. However, when the outbreak had decreased to a less-intense transmission rate, it helped eliminate the disease.]

5 Nov 2015: NIBSC Ebola reference reagents endorsed as global standards by WHO
https://www.gov.uk/government/news/nibsc-ebola-reference-reagents-endorsed-as-global-standards-by-who
[Ebola reference reagents produced by the National Institute for Biological Standards and Control (NIBSC) have been endorsed as the global standards for use in laboratory tests by the World Health Organization (WHO) Expert Committee on Biological Standardization, and are now available to the scientific community. NIBSC was asked by WHO to produce 2 types of Ebola virus reference reagents. The first reagent is run alongside patient samples to detect Ebola virus disease (EVD) infection. The second measures EVD antibody levels following infection, or following immunization with candidate vaccines. The Ebola antibody standard will be used around the world in the testing of Ebola vaccines in development, and is expected to help accelerate the availability of new vaccines for EVD.]

5 Nov 2015 Canada: Medicago to develop Sudan strain Ebola antibodies
http://globalbiodefense.com/2015/11/05/medicago-to-develop-sudan-strain-ebola-antibodies/
[Public Health Agency of Canada (PHAC) has awarded new funding to Medicago, a plant-based biopharmaceutical company, to develop two antibodies to fight the Sudan strain of the Ebola virus. The Ebola Sudan strain has been previously associated with large outbreaks in Africa.]

6 Nov 2015: Grantees selected to build Ebola research capacity
http://www.edctp.org/news/grantees-selected-build-ebola-research-capacity/
[6 institutions in Africa and Europe have been awarded funding to strengthen capacity in sub-Saharan Africa to conduct high-quality health research during health emergencies and/or epidemic outbreaks. The grants were developed in response to the Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak in West Africa, and they address individual, institutional, national and regional capacity.
3 recipients are based in Africa and 3 are in Europe, working in Africa and with African partners. The scope of the projects ranges from improving capacity for clinical trials to health system rebuilding. The European and Developing Countries Clinical Trials Partnership (EDCTP) and TDR are providing the EUR 1.49 million (USD 1.61 million) funding.]

[compiled by: Celeste Whitlow <whitlow.celeste@gmail.com>]
